{
  "texts": [
    "The technological progression within artificial intelligence, especially when it comes to the realm of natural language processing, has ignited significant discussions about how closely large language models (LLMs), including chatbots like ChatGPT, emulate human linguistic cognition and utilization (Chomsky, Roberts, & Watumull, 2023; Piantadosi, 2023; Binz and Schulz; 2023).",
    "With each technological leap, distinguishing between human linguistic cognition and the capabilities of AI-driven language models becomes even more intricate (Wilcox et al., 2022; Van Schijndel & Linzen, 2018; Futrell et al., 2019).",
    "This leads scholars to query if these LLMs genuinely reflect human linguistic nuances or merely reproduce them on a cosmetic level (Cai et al., 2023).",
    "This research delves deeper into the congruencies and disparities between LLMs and humans, focusing primarily on their instinctive understanding of grammar.",
    "In three preregistered experiments, ChatGPT was asked to provide grammaticality judgement in different formats for over two thousand sentences with diverse structural configurations."
  ]
}